segments.text: No, I sure don't.
I haven't found any positive responses to that question.
Now, often people, sometimes journalists talk about a military mentality.
Do you think there's a military mentality, and if so, what is it?
I don't really know about that.
That would be hard for me to really.
distinguish that.
I'm a little lost on that one.
I just can't see where they, I don't see why, how they get that.
You've heard of that term though haven't you?
I'm not sure I have.
Yeah I guess, I guess I know what you're talking about.
I might not have heard it called military mentality.
I may have heard it say that he's got a military way or some such thing, which to me is not really a fault.
It may be an attribute.
No, I'm not saying that at all.
Okay, let's move on then.
When you became an A&M graduate officer,
Did you find that the what did you find was the quality of the officers that graduated?
Especially after you got out in the field.
Now do you mean after I How good was the training here at A&M for officers?
I think a good

a good description of it was what I told you a while ago this colonel comes back who's not an Aggie and picks vast majority of Aggies for this particular unit that he commanded when he was given the selection of who he wanted to serve in this unit and I think everywhere that I went the feeling was that the Aggies were well trained
ROTC officers.

In fact, I've heard some remarks, not personally, but in printed materials and whatnot, of some of the top men in World War II, the top military people, that have had most high remarks from A&M officers.
What do you think West Pointers think of A&M officers?
I can tell you what they think.
They don't think very highly of them.
They don't?
I mean, it's a jealousy.
I think if they were real sincere, they would tell you that they've made good officers, but there's a jealousy between the West Point and the ROTCs, at least that's what I found.
Did you explain this jealousy?
Why are they jealous?
Well, one thing I think, because there's so darn many more of us,

and uh well Aggie officers were down-to-earth officers I mean I think we had a lot of good common sense and a lot of the West Pointers were so military oriented and so so the West Point oriented and all of them I mean
Every one of them are trying their darndest to get up another one on the ladder.
And every cockeyed thing they do is, I mean, it's headed for what's in the future for them.
And I think the philosophy of that is even though we always wanted to excel and get to be higher levels,
I think our aim more was to do a good job and then those things would take care of themselves.
The West Pointer, he can't think of anything but the darn star.
And I mean, he'll trample you to death to get there.
And their social activities, their whole life is centered around, you know,
Kissing the general's wife or whatever, you know.
Promotion?
Yeah, sure.
I mean, that's from morning till night.
Now, there are exceptions, I'm sure, but their general philosophy is, boy, how high can I get?
And I think the ROTC officer is the only thing about doing a good job and those things take care of themselves.
Did you know a lot of West Pointers?
Yes, I did.
I suppose you have.
And how could you compare the training that they've had versus our training?
Well, all the ones that I saw, of course, their technical training probably exceeded ours.
Your technical military training?
Yes, that's correct.
Their technical...

civilian training or their technical administrative training or their day-to-day courses that they took probably were not to the level of ours but of course the service academies of course dwell on the military subjects they did a great deal more military subjects than ROTC officers so
So they've been exposed to a great deal more.
But the general rule of them, they feel that too.
And they want you to know that too.
They don't make any bones about it.
And that's darn near without exception.
That is the ones I've run into.
In other words, you think there's some friction between the A&M men and the West Point men?
There sure were.
There was throughout your career.
Yeah.
Something that's real funny, and it's part of the down-to-earthness that I'm talking about.
Of course, the Aggies have always been known for their table manners in the mess halls, which are not according to Emily Post or some of those, and the West Pointers despise that.
Well, you know, it's not...
It's not the best in the world, but it's part of that camaraderie and esprit de corps and all this.
They have their own way of doing this sort of thing.
When we first went on active duty, if you used the mess hall lingo and asked a West Pointer to shoot the gunwiden or to pass the sandan or whatever, he would absolutely ignore you.

Now, he knew exactly what you were saying, but they would not only just, you know, you would think they'd just pass it and sort of ignore you and all this, but I mean, they wouldn't pass you anything unless you asked them to pass the bread or pass the salt and pepper.
And that sort of thing just really put us on different courses.
And when I was first called active duty, we had out of the

hundred officers in this regiment we had about five west pointers and they were really with one exception they were just sort of outcasts we just would not have much to do with them and it's bad that is a bad situation and we are much to blame as they are but we were one direction and they're the other see they're they're you know just
Straight down the line, and of course we, you know.
In other words, you'd say that we're probably more pragmatic.
Is that what we're grasping for?
I guess.
Or is that, I don't want to put words in your mouth.
Well, the, we were always so, so close to each other that

that we you know whatever it took to get along and to help you fellow man and to to be a down-to-earth person this is what you're saying and they're instilled that you know they're they're officers and gentlemen by an act of congress and yeah and I think I just never really saw a great deal of exception to that I mean

after they after they got on up to be generals and whatnot they lost a little bit of that separation but we used to we used to have lots of discussion about it and we did it in a friendly manner but there is a difference a great difference.
Now when you graduated let's talk about when you graduated did you have did you have firm aims
to go into civilian engineering?
Yes.
No thought about going into the military as a profession?
Uh, there were not, first place, there were not but very few opportunities at that time.
There were some officers that went in under what they called a Thomas Nag, which was a one-year program.
Yeah.
and many of them ultimately became regular army but I didn't really have any aspirations for that at all and I guess with my thinking military might wonder why but
I was interested in getting out and starting engineering and get on that course.

If there had been numerous Thomason Act opportunities, it might have been different, but and I think they took probably the top ROTC students as far as the military subjects they'd taken and there was probably a little politics in it too, I expect.
but I really never gave it up.
Then let's start with your academic career.
We haven't even started talking about your academics here at A&M.
We know why you wanted to go into engineering school and why you came here.
What, what some of the faculty, who are some of the faculty or staff that had an impact on you?
Well there was a
Well in the C.E.
department named McNew.
McNew.
Right.
And there was an old gentleman who was just in the last year passed away named Sandstedt.
S-A-N-D-S-T-E-D-T who was a great old gentleman.
All the C.E.
students loved him.
I had a math professor named McGee, Roger McGee, that I thought was real terrific.
And of course we got on up into the structures and hydraulics and this sort of thing.
Fred Benson out there at A&M was a young, I presume he was a graduate student about the time I was there.
Everybody thought Fred Benson was a fine teacher.

Uh there was an old fellow that uh that ran the mechanical engineering shops that taught me a class or two named Walter Downer that was you know you had people that you think golly I sure wish I could do that sort of thing sometime you know.
They were that tight?
Yeah and

then the man who was head of ME department at that time uh it's still here in Bryan that taught me a few classes that you remember you remember them well like we always thought that they were interested in teaching you that they were interested in you you're grasping their subjects and not not just being there for spend an hour with you so they were I had a great many of them
Had another one that taught me history.
Count Chigarth.
Have you ever heard of him?
Yeah.
General Butler was telling me about him.
The clown.
Well you know he got his subjects over well because he remembered him.

and and Jolly he was a Russian actually he was a immigrant I think he had to get out of some part of Russia for the Sadie's Island or whatever where he got the name Count I really don't know but uh talking holy lords Mr. Hanover but some of those you know that really
I don't know that that was any attribute they had, but darn you remember the fellow.
You ask him a question that happened to be wrong, he'd say, Mr. Hanover, where did you get that answer?
Well, I thought I got it out of the book count.
The book's no damn good.
throw it out the window and say, well, you know, it's just wild, but you learn from it.
What did you think of the quality of education?
Well, I'm not sure that I was evaluating it at that time.
Well, let's say after you got out in the field of being a professional engineer.
I thought it was pretty darn good.
Okay, and you met people from other engineering schools across the state and country.
That's right.
And, you know, I've talked with a lot of people who've gone to other schools.
You know, what did you do in summer survey?
How did you get along in analytic geometry and this sort of thing?
I think we stacked up very well.
I was always pleased to see how he graduated me and him.
There were a lot of there were a good many teachers that I had back in those times that that I thought

knew their subjects well but were a little a little weak on being able to present it which gosh you're going to have that any time but then the ones who who did either I got it well or they put it over well those are the ones you remember and I had a chemistry teacher who knew his subject I'm sure backward and forward
But he had a heavy German brogue, and I had not had any chemistry in high school.
And I knew from the time I'd been in there, two weeks, that I wasn't gonna pass it.
And he geared his education to those who had had high school chemistry.

and I presume if I had asked him to spend some extra time with me he probably would have but a freshman you're reluctant to ask them to do this sort of thing or at least I sure seem to be sure and I failed it I knew I was going to fail it but I stayed in there and I know I learned something turned right around in the summer and took it again and made a B out of it but I got a different professor
You know I laid a lot of that failure to communication.
Yeah.
And I've told a lot of people about that over the years and I was several others that had that same fellow experienced the same thing I did.
Of course when I was a freshman so they told me they were 60 percent of my freshman class that failed freshman chemistry and that is too high.
Yeah.

there's some problems that ain't all the students yeah but anyway speaking speaking of the students what do you think of the quality of the student colleagues that you have well I thought of course at that time uh not everybody wanted to go to college and win I'm sure oh yeah so I guess maybe we had a little cut above
what you would say was just across the board desire to go to college.
And I was, I thought we had an awfully good group of students.
The ones I came in direct contact with, I made some friends that I still have today.
So, you know, I think we, I think we did pretty well.
I guess, I guess they were a good, better than average.
Now often, I've heard coming down to Texas A&M that there's, that this is more than an institution of higher learning, that it's something special.
What do you think about that?
Yeah, I really think it is.
Could you define what it is that's special about it, about your feelings?
Yeah, I think part of it is the students that go there, and the relationship that develops when they're there.

and the relationship now I've got to be speaking from back yonder because we're talking about the late 30s and I think there was a there was a relationship between students and the teachers that was good I think that as I said a while ago these these folks that that had a keen interest in me

They wanted to see you do what held you up and of course as I moved up through the years most of my work was in the CE department and we had people that had been out in the industry and they were able to tell you firsthand about construction problems and financial problems and public relations problems

production problems and this sort of thing so I think that that relationship generated this closeness to the students and then you know as a snowball rolls it gets bigger and it it makes itself and I think from way back there
This relationship that the students have and the former students with the university, I think that makes it a unique university.
I think it's just got qualities that, at least from back in my family, I think it's got qualities that stay with you.

and makes you want to meet others that have been there and when you see one you feel you've really got something coming so it's sort of a camaraderie there too that's right is that what they mean when they talk about spirit yeah that's right are there other aspects of this spirit
Oh, of course it would have lots of aspects to it, but I think it's that thing that this ring is the trademark.
You can see an Aggie across the room, if you've got a ring on you recognize it and know something about it that you look for.
In fact, every time I meet anybody with a class ring on, I have to take a look at it.
and it doesn't matter if this whole top's worn off you see it's an Aggie ring and I don't know they just there are people that that condemn that aspect saying you know you're clannish and you're
If you're not an Aggie, you're not any part of the crowd and all this sort of thing.
I guess I can understand why people say that, but we on the inside feel that it's great.
Okay.
To each his own, you know.
Right.
And what way do you think that A&M changed your life?
Oh, of course it gave me a degree and put me on the road to a career that was very satisfying, of course.
It started my military career.
It gave me an appreciation for work because I had a job there when I needed it to go to school.
It taught me the value of work.
It taught me the value of people who were interested in me.
We had a fellow who supervised student labor out there.
His name was Horsley.
And that man treated us like we were his boys.
I mean, he wanted you to work, but he was the coordinator of all the student labor.
And he had just as much interest in me as he would if I hadn't been Horsley.
And that

that just has stayed with me and here's people that are interested in students, interested in people getting along, getting a job, doing something that makes it available for them to go to school and of course the some of the professors down there as I say are still
still treasures to me and it just I guess gave me the platform to spring from.

Of course the academic experiences gave me the it didn't make me a darn bit better than a man out there who who had worked and come up through the ranks but it gave me something an ability to excel and get past that fellow
down the road.
When I got out and went to work, I was put under the supervision of a fellow who was seven, eight, ten years older than I.
Never had a day of college in his life, didn't graduate from high school, but he was, he could figure in his head faster than I could figure on a calculator.
And he ran a survey crew,
and he knew a world of the basics of engineering and he taught them to me.

He learned his through the hard knock school and he couldn't take a book and work a calculus problem, he couldn't take a book and work a trigonometry problem, but he could work any problem he needed to run a survey crew.
But I was put under him and what he told me to do by George I did.
or I would have been out on the street.
And I learned to respect the grandfather people.
I'm talking about the people who come up here that way.
But it wasn't long until he was under me, and I was directing him, and he respected that.
Because he knew that I had technical training, I had college training, and we had no problem.
But I started out right under him.

And I think and I saw a number of people who did not come from A&M that went to work for us put him under that fella and they thought right off that that was a degradation of their abilities and capabilities and they took offense to it and it didn't last long.

now that's there are exceptions to that too but we learned as I've indicated a time or two we learned to respect authority and jurisdiction and when the higher man said you're working for this fellow that's what he was I didn't question it but
my technical ability and my will to excel it wasn't long before I moved on.
Okay as soon as you graduated and and then the period before you went into the service before you were called back to duty tell me about that occupation.
Well I went to work for the highway department.
Okay.
As a they called it a rodman I was just a flunky to the to the survey crew and we were

We were going out and we were chaining and cutting brush and staking out highway construction projects and just wanted to follow the group you know and learn it from the ground even though I had taken surveys in the evening.
That's right just like putting a
a man on an oil rig who graduated from A&M, you know, you want him to learn it from the floor up.
My boss said, you're starting at the ground.

So I did that and then after a few months, my boss put me in the office and I was doing a little plan work because I could calculate and I could balance dirt and I could lay grade lines and I could calculate estimates and this sort of thing.
But that's about as far as I got because I only worked nine months.
and what called the service.
So I really just sort of got in on the ground floor and was able to sort of establish myself and show him that I wanted to work and that whatever he gave me to do, I wanted to try to learn it.
And what responsibility he said I was to take, that was it.
Now this is 1940 and the economy was starting to pick up with the war going on in Europe.
Were there other alternatives besides the highway, any other alternatives for jobs that you might have had any opportunities?
There were a good many, I say a good many, there were some contractors that came to A&M to hire civil engineers.
Several of the steel fabricating companies wanted engineers.
A lot of them working on defense industries?
I presume, and then just designers,
The aircraft industry was beginning to hire engineers.
The highway department had a standing offer.
They would take all the engineers who graduated from A&M in Texas.
Really?
Yeah, see they were, we were, the highway department was beginning to get monies to expand their operations after World War II.
But we, anybody, any civil engineer that wanted to go to work for the highway department when I graduated could go to work.
Why'd you decide on them instead of other occupations?
Because of this thing that I was telling you before, road work fascinated me.
Yeah, okay, okay.
Seeing something done from nothing to a finished product.
Right, right.
And I really never even gave a thought to any other type of engineering but highway.
and I took a good many elective highway engineering courses so my air was just headed in that direction.
Okay I say let's continue tomorrow.
That's great.
Okay.
